O God! Thou art my God alone;  
Within the quiet hush of dawn,  
My spirit lifts, my soul is drawn  
To rest upon Thy holy throne.  

Thou art the lamp that lights the way,  
The breath upon the greying sea;  
My rock in strife, my refuge stay,  
The hand that gently shepherds me.  

When night grows deep and shadows fall,  
In silent trust I find resource;  
For Thou hast heard my yearning call,  
And guide me on with patient force.  

O sovereign Lord, my joy, my peace!  
Each breath I take is Thine bestown;  
My deepest hunger Thou canst cease;  
O God! Thou art my God alone.

I always see to it—the kettle rising, hush and steam;
The unlatched window for your dreams, breathing silver in the air—
I bear the innumerable small tender things quietly required;
Every leaf-creased note, each button mended, every doorstep clear of snow so morning feels desired.
Just enough: hands finding their purpose—I tend so stillness dwells within the sway;
Both anchor and wind, unnoticed tendril, gentle earth for you around each lifeworn day.

Soldier, wake – the day is peeping,
Tumult stirs where morning blooms;
Hues of orange tented, sweeping
Cast away the night's oppressing gloom.
Chain and buckle, boots and reason;
Breath held fast between alike --
Men together knell this season,
Painted faces, courage spiked.
Sun awash with warbler singing,
Hope and dread so closely keeping;
Still at duty, bells are ringing;
Soldier, wake — the day is peeping.

Shall I, wasting in despair, cradle shadows in thin hands,
Or sketch sadness on the air, marking loss where it now stands?
No—let not sorrow be my guide, nor let longing wear my days;
For though the rose oft withers, dried, memory shows streaks of blaze.
Let hope offer gentle light, gentle hands ease heavy care;
If fools are those who clutch at night, let them roam—I shall repair
My fortune with each gained dawn, cast my tears upon the sea;
Time rolls sighs and dreams along—hope remains enough for me.

We sink into the dust—
A final act, unhurried, slow;
Flesh turning memory, longing dissolving in low glow.
Wind will swirl our laughter, forgotten words adrift;
Yet tender hope takes root above and finds a form to lift.
Nature tucks us not away, but deep where stories spin;
In dust, we seed tomorrow, soft worlds sprouting from within.

Light breaks where no sun shines;  
Miracles in the marrow of stone—  
Roots whisper, water threads their designs,  
Life preparing in the cold, alone.

Winter-hard sinews lift bowers unseen,  
Veins of quartz pulse beneath closed eyes;  
Radiance lingers in vales between—  
Faint narratives stitched where silence lies.

From absence, new brightness kindles unaware,  
Unwritten wonders trespass through the gloom—
We find seed, note wordless hope whispered there;
Even night hands open, they shimmer, they bloom0Traces of morning, birthed in deepest mines; 
Still, light breaks bravely where no sun shines.
